<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910809-0142</DOCNO><DOCID>910809-0142.</DOCID><HL>   Texas Utilities   Taking a Charge   Of $1 Billion   ----   By Patricia Ann McKanic   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3</SO><CO>   TXU</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)</IN><NS>NUCLEAR POWER, ENERGY (NUK)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Texas Utilities Co. said it would take a $1 billionthird-quarter charge after regulators rejected its attemptsto recoup certain costs associated with its Comanche Peaknuclear power plant.   The charge will mean a significant loss for the year, theDallas-based utility said. In the third quarter a yearearlier, net income was $344.7 million, or $1.77 a share, onrevenue of $1.41 billion.</LP><TEXT>   A company spokesman said the extent of the loss for 1991isn't yet determinable. The $1 billion charge equals about $5a share.   The regulators ruled that Texas Utilities cannot pass onto its customers some $1.38 billion in costs related to itsComanche Peak plant, under construction for the past 17years.   The ruling by the Public Utility Commission of Texas, alsogrants the utility the full $442 million or 10% annualrevenue increase it had sought and orders it to refund to itscustomers a total of $48 million, related to fuel purchasesfor a six-year period beginning in 1983.   Texas Utilities said that it would initiate immediatebelt-tightening measures, including cutting costs, freezinghiring and possibly further postponing construction at somepower plants.   In late composite trading on the New York Stock Exchangeyesterday, Texas Utilities stock was quoted at $37.75, down50 cents.   So far, construction costs on the Comanche Peak planttotal $10.7 billion, with yet only one unit of the2300-megawatt facility completed and operating. The plant is75 miles southwest of Dallas. The company expects to spend anadditional $800 million to bring Unit 2 of the plant intoservice by the summer of 1993.   Texas Utilities became sole owner of Comanche Peak afterbuying out the interests of three other partners to settlelitigation against the company.</TEXT></DOC>